# Mermaid Diagram Documentation Pattern

When adding or editing Mermaid diagrams in documentation:

## 1. Render to PNG

- Save the diagram to `docs/images/<descriptive-name>.mmd` (or a `.mmd` file next to the doc).
- Render with mermaid-cli: `npx @mermaid-js/mermaid-cli -i docs/images/<name>.mmd -o docs/images/<name>.png -e png`
- Use a descriptive filename (e.g. `pipeline-high-level`, `dependency-graph`).

## 2. Document Structure

Place the rendered image first, then the Mermaid source in a collapsible section (default closed):

```markdown
![Alt text for diagram](images/diagram-name.png)

<details>
<summary>Mermaid source</summary>

```mermaid
flowchart TB
  ...
```
</details>
```

## 3. Rules

- **Image first** — Readers see the diagram immediately.
- **Collapsible source** — Use `<details><summary>Mermaid source</summary>` so the Mermaid code is hidden by default; users can expand to view or copy.
- **Both always present** — Never add only the image or only the Mermaid; include both.
- **Consistent paths** — For docs in `docs/`, use relative paths like `images/diagram-name.png`.

## 4. Example

Structure to follow:

1. Heading or caption
2. `![alt](images/name.png)` — rendered image
3. `<details><summary>Mermaid source</summary>` — collapsible (closed by default)
4. Mermaid fenced block with the diagram
5. `</details>`
